# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: philadelphia
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:philadelphia/1790-united-states-census] The **1790 United States census** was the first United States census.
[src:philadelphia/1790-united-states-census] It recorded the population of the whole United States as of Census Day, August 2, 1790, as mandated by Article 1, Section 2, of the Constitution and applicable laws.
[src:philadelphia/1790-united-states-census] In the first census, the population of the United States was enumerated to be 3,929,214 inhabitants.
[src:philadelphia/1790-united-states-census] Congress assigned responsibility for the 1790 census to the marshals of United States judicial districts under an act, which with minor modifications and extensions, governed census taking through the 1840 census.
[src:philadelphia/1790-united-states-census] Both Secretary of State Thomas Jefferson and President George Washington expressed skepticism over the results, believing that the true population had been undercounted.
[src:philadelphia/1790-united-states-census] If indeed an undercount was the result, possible explanations for it include dispersed population, poor transportation links, limitations of contemporary technology, and individual refusal to participate.
[src:philadelphia/1790-united-states-census] Although the census was proved statistically factual, based on data collected, the records for several states (including Delaware, Georgia, New Jersey, and Virginia) were lost sometime between 1790 and 1830.
[src:philadelphia/1790-united-states-census] Almost one-third of the original census data have been lost or destroyed since their original documentation.
[src:philadelphia/1790-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1790 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:philadelphia/1790-united-states-census] The census was not conducted in Vermont until 1791, after that state's admission to the Union as the 14th state on March 4 of that year.
[src:philadelphia/1790-united-states-census] At 17.8 percent, the 1790 census's proportion of slaves to the free population was the highest ever recorded by any census of the United States.
[src:philadelphia/1790-united-states-census] 0 is the correct figure, and the 16 here should be added to the "All other free persons" column.
[src:philadelphia/1790-united-states-census] When the census of 1790 was published in 1791, it reported 16 slaves, which were illegal in Vermont.
[src:philadelphia/1790-united-states-census] Subsequently, and up to 1860, the number is given as 17.
[src:philadelphia/1790-united-states-census] An examination of the original manuscript by the Census Bureau superintendent found that there never were any slaves in Vermont.
[src:philadelphia/1790-united-states-census] The original error occurred in preparing the results for publication, when 16 persons, returned as "Free colored," were classified as "Slave" in Bennington County.
[src:philadelphia/1790-united-states-census] Corrected figures are 85,425, or 114 less than figures published in 1790, due to an error of addition of several towns.
[src:philadelphia/1790-united-states-census] Corrected figures are 59,096, or 2 more than figures published in 1790, due to error in addition.
[src:philadelphia/1790-united-states-census] The figures for Virginia do not include the population of Kentucky.
[src:philadelphia/1790-united-states-census] Though Kentucky was then a part of Virginia, the Kentucky figures were compiled separately, and are shown on the line for Kentucky.
[src:philadelphia/1790-united-states-census] The Virginia figures do include the portion of Virginia that later became the state of West Virginia.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] The **Philadelphia 1793 yellow fever epidemic** was an epidemic that took place in Philadelphia.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] During the epidemic, 5,000 or more people died between August 1 and November 9.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] The vast majority of them died of yellow fever, making the epidemic in the city of 50,000 people, one of the most severe in United States history.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] By the end of September, 20,000 people had fled the city, including congressional and executive officials of the federal government of the United States.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Most did not return until after the epidemic had abated in late November.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] The mortality rate peaked in October before frost finally killed the mosquitoes and brought an end to the outbreak.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Doctors tried a variety of treatments but knew neither the origin of the fever nor that the disease was transmitted by mosquitoes (this information was not verified until the late 19th century).
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Matthew Clarkson, the mayor of Philadelphia, and a committee of two dozen organized a fever hospital at Bush Hill and other crisis measures.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] The assistance of the Free African Society was requested by the city and readily agreed to by its members.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Parties mistakenly assumed that people of African descent would have partial immunity to the new disease.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Black nurses aided the sick, and the group's leaders hired additional men to take away corpses, which most people would not touch.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] But black people in the city died at the same rate as whites, about 240 altogether.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Some neighboring towns refused to let refugees in from Philadelphia, fearing that they were carrying the fever.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Major port cities, including Baltimore and New York City, had quarantines against refugees and goods from Philadelphia, although New York City sent financial aid to Philadelphia.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] In the spring of 1793, French colonial refugees, some with slaves, arrived from Cap Français, Saint-Domingue, in present-day Haiti.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] The 2,000 immigrants fled the slave revolution in the island's north.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] They crowded the port of Philadelphia, where the first yellow fever epidemic in the city in 30 years began.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] It is likely that the refugees and ships carried the yellow fever virus and mosquitoes.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Mosquitoes easily breed in small amounts of standing water.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] The medical community and others in 1793 did not understand the role of mosquitoes in the transmission of yellow fever, malaria, and other diseases.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] In the ports and coastal areas of the United States, even in the northeast, the months of August and September were considered the "sickly season," when fevers were prevalent.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] In the South, planters and other wealthy people usually left the Low Country during this season.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Natives thought that newcomers, especially, had to undergo a "seasoning" and were more likely to die of what were thought to be seasonal fevers in their early years in the region.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] In 1793, Philadelphia was the temporary capital of the United States, and the government was due to return in the fall.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] President George Washington left the city for his Mount Vernon estate.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] The first two people to die of yellow fever in early August in Philadelphia were both recent immigrants, one from Ireland and the other from Saint-Domingue.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Letters describing their cases were published in a pamphlet approximately a month after they died.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] The young doctor sent by the Overseers of the Poor to treat the Irish woman was perplexed, and his treatment did not save her.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Smith, professor of history at Montana State University, makes a case that the principal vector of the 1793 plague in Philadelphia (and other Atlantic ports) was the British merchant ship *Hankey*, which had fled the West African island colony on Bolama the previous November.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] It trailed yellow fever at every port of call in the Caribbean and eastern Atlantic seaboard.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Benjamin Rush was a doctor's apprentice during the city's 1762 yellow fever epidemic, and after two weeks and an increasing number of fever cases, he recognized the pattern.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Rush alerted his colleagues and the government that the city faced an outbreak of "highly contagious, as well as mortal... bilious remitting yellow fever." Adding to the alarm was that, unlike with most fevers, the principal victims were not very young or very old.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Many of the early deaths were teenagers and heads of families in the dockside areas.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Believing that the refugees from Saint-Domingue were carrying the disease, the city imposed a quarantine of two to three weeks on immigrants and their goods.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Stillit was unable to enforce it as the epidemic spread further.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Philadelphia was the largest city in the US, with around 50,000 residents, and most houses were within seven blocks of its major port on the Delaware River—docking facilities extended from Southwark south of the city, to Kensington to the north.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Cases of fever clustered at first around the Arch Street wharf.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Rush blamed "some damaged coffee which putrefied on the wharf near Arch Street" for causing the fevers.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] As the port was critical to the state's economy, Pennsylvania Governor Thomas Mifflin had responsibility for its health.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] James Hutchinson, to assess the conditions.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Rush later described some early cases: On August 7, he treated a young man for headaches, fever, and vomiting, and on August 15 he treated his brother.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] On the same day, a woman he was treating turned a yellowish color.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] On August 18 a man on the third day of fever had no pulse, was cold, clammy, and yellow, but he could sit up in his bed.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] On August 19 a woman Rush visited died within hours.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Another physician said five people within sight of her door died.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] None of those victims was a recent immigrant.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] The college published a letter in the city's newspapers, written by a committee headed by Rush, suggesting 11 measures to prevent the "progress" of the fever.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] They warned citizens avoid unnecessary contact with people who are sick and to avoid fatigue, the hot sun, cold night air, excessive drinking, and anything else that might lower their resistance.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Crews were sent to clean the wharves, streets, and the market, which cheered those remaining in the city.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Elizabeth Drinker, a Quaker woman, kept a journal for years; her account from August 23 through August 30 tells the story of the disease's rapid spread in the city and the rising toll of deaths.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] She also describes the many people leaving the city.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Like all hospitals of that time, the Pennsylvania Hospital did not admit patients with infectious diseases.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] The Guardians of the Poor took over Bush Hill, a 150-acre estate farther outside the city, whose owner, William Hamilton, was in England for an extended stay.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Vice President John Adams had recently rented the main house, so yellow fever patients were placed in the outbuildings.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Between the college's advisory on August 25 and the death of Dr.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Hutchinson from yellow fever on September 7, panic spread throughout the city; more people fled.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Between August 1 and September 7, 456 people died in the city; 42 deaths were reported on September 8.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] An estimated 20,000 people left the city through September, including national leaders.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] The daily death toll remained above 30 until October 26.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] The worst seven-day period was between October 7 and 13, when 711 deaths were reported.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] The College of Physicians' advisory implied the fever was contagious and people should avoid contact with its victims, although "duty" required that they be cared for.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Yet in families, when the person with the fever was a mother or father, they could forbid their children from coming near them.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] John Lining's observation during the 1742 yellow fever epidemic in Charleston, South Carolina, that African slaves appeared to be affected at rates lower than Whites; he thought they had a natural immunity.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Allen notes in his account that because of the increase in mortality, he and Jones had to hire five men to assist them in removing corpses, as most people avoided the sick and the dead.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] In a September 6 letter to his wife, Rush writes the "African brethren ... furnish nurses to most of my patients." Despite Rush's theory, most of the city's black residents, who were born in North America, were not immune to the fever.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Many of the slaves in Charleston in 1742 could have gained immunity before having been transported from Africa, by having been exposed to yellow fever in a mild case.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] People who survived one attack gained immunity.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] A total of 240 blacks died in Philadelphia, in proportion to their population at the same rate as whites.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Given the limited resources and knowledge of the times, the city's response was credible.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] The medical community did not know the natural history of yellow fever, a viral infection spread by the *Aedes aegypti* mosquito.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Efforts to clean the city did not defeat the spread of the fever, as the mosquitoes breed in clean water as well as in dirty water.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Philadelphia's newspapers continued to publish during the epidemic, and doctors and other health professionals worked to understand and combat the disease.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Adam Kuhn, who had studied medicine at the University of Uppsala in Sweden, advised patients to treat symptoms as they arose.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Rush claimed that he had tried Kuhn's and Steven's stimulating remedies but that his patients still died.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] He recommended other treatments, including purging and bloodletting, and published his theories.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] The hope offered by any of these treatments was soon dashed when it became clear that they did not cure the disease, and the doctors' competing claims demoralized patients.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Allen and Jones wrote that they were thankful that "we have been the instruments, in the hand of God, for saving the lives of hundreds of our suffering fellow mortals." Rush's brand of medicine became the standard American treatment for fevers in the 1790s and was widely used for the next 50 years.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Rush's claim that his remedies cured 99 out of 100 patients has led historians and modern doctors to ridicule his remedies and approach to medical science.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] The newspaper editor William Cobbett attacked Rush's therapies and called him a *Sangrado*, after a character in *Gil Blas*, who bled patients to death.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] The state legislature cut short its September session after a dead body was found on the steps of the State House.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Governor Mifflin became ill and was advised by his doctor to leave.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] The city's banks remained open, but banking operations were so slowed by the inability of people to pay off notes because of disruptions from the epidemic that banks automatically renewed notes until the epidemic ended.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Mayor Matthew Clarkson organized the city's response to the epidemic.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Most of the Common Council members fled, along with 20,000 other residents.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] People who did not leave Philadelphia before the second week in September could leave the city only with great difficulty, and they faced roadblocks, patrols, inspections, and quarantines.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] On September 12, Clarkson summoned fellow citizens interested in helping the Guardians of the Poor.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] They formed a committee to take over from the Guardians and address the crisis.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] On September 14 Clarkson was joined by 26 men who formed committees to reorganize the fever hospital, arrange visits to the sick, feed those unable to care for themselves, and arrange for wagons to carry the sick to the hospital and the dead to Potter's Field.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] After a report of 15-month-old twins being orphaned, two days later, the committee had identified a house for sheltering the growing number of orphans.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] When the Committee inspected the Bush Hill fever hospital, they found the nurses to be unqualified and the arrangements to be chaotic.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] "The sick, the dying, and the dead were indiscriminately mingled together.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] The ordure and other evacuations of the sick were allowed to remain in the most offensive state imaginable...
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] It was, in fact, a great human slaughter-house." On September 15 Peter Helm, a barrel maker, and Stephen Girard, a merchant and shipowner born in France, volunteered to manage the hospital and represent the Committee personally.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] They made rapid improvements in hospital operations: bedsteads were repaired, and more were brought from the prison so patients would not have to lie on the floor.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] A barn was converted into a convalescent facility for patients.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] On September 17, the managers hired 9 female nurses and 10 male attendants, as well as a female matron.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] They assigned the 14 rooms to separate male and female patients.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] With the discovery of a spring on the estate, workers were organized to have clean water pumped into the hospital.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Helm and Girard informed the Committee that they could accommodate more than the 60 patients then under their care, and soon the hospital had 140 patients.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Girard found that the intermittent visits by 4 young physicians from the city added to the confusion about patient treatment.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] He hired Jean Devèze, a French doctor with experience treating yellow fever in Saint-Domingue.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Devèze cared only for the patients at the hospital, and French apothecaries assisted him.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Devèze admired Girard's fearlessness in his devotion to the patients.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] News that patients treated at the hospital were recovering encouraged many people to believe that medicine was gaining control of the fever, but it soon became clear that mortality at the hospital remained high; about 50% of those admitted died.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] As the death toll in the city rose, officials in neighboring communities and major port cities such as New York and Baltimore established quarantines for refugees and goods from Philadelphia.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] New York established a "Committee appointed to prevent the spreading and introduction of infectious diseases in this city", which set up citizen patrols to monitor entry to the city.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Stage coaches from Philadelphia were not allowed in many cities.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Havre de Grace, Maryland, for example, tried to prevent people from Philadelphia from crossing the Susquehanna River to Maryland.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Neighboring cities did send food supplies and money; for example, New York City sent $5000 ($119,000 in 2025) to the Mayor's Committee.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Woodbury and Springfield, New Jersey; Chester, Pennsylvania and Elkton, Maryland, were among towns that accepted refugees.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] In his 1793 account of the epidemic, Mathew Carey contrasts the sacrifices of men like Joseph Inskeep, a Quaker who served on the Mayor's Committee and also visited the sick, with the selfishness of others.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] When Inskeep contracted the fever, he asked for the assistance of a family whom he had attended when several of its members were sick.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] He died, which might well have happened even if they had aided him.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Carey published rumours of greed, especially by landlords who threw convalescing tenants into the street to gain control of their flats.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] While he praises Allen and Jones for their work, he suggests that blacks had caused the epidemic and that some black nurses had charged high fees and even stole from those for whom they cared.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Allen and Jones quickly wrote a pamphlet to defend people of colour in the crisis.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Historian Julie Winch believes they wanted to defend their community, knowing the power of Carey, and to maintain the reputation of their people in the aftermath of the epidemic.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] The men note that the first nurses from the Free African Society had worked without any pay.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] As the mortality rate increased, they had to hire men to deal with the sick and dying.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Allen and Jones note that white nurses also profited and stole from their patients.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Church clergy continued to hold services, which helped keep up residents' morale.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Helmuth, who led the city's German Lutheran congregation, wrote *A Short Account of the Yellow Fever in Philadelphia for the Reflecting Christian.* He also left a diary.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] On September 16, he reported that his church was "very full" the day before.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] In a single week in October, 130 members of his congregation were buried.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] The Yearly Meeting of the Society of Friends at the Arch Street Meeting House drew 100 attendees, most from outside the city.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] The meetinghouse is not far from the waterfront where the epidemic had started.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] In their Yearly Epistle following the meeting, the Friends wrote that to have changed the time or place of the meeting would have been a "haughty attempt" to escape "the rod" of God, from which there was no escape.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Quaker John Todd, who attended the meeting, contracted the fever and died of it.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] His young widow, Dolley Payne Todd, later married James Madison, a Virginia congressman whom she met in Philadelphia and who later was elected as US president.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Philadelphia native Anne Parrish devoted herself to philanthropy after the epidemic, founding the Female Society for the Relief of the Distressed in 1795.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Doctors, preachers, and laymen all looked to the coming of autumn to end the epidemic.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] At first they hoped a seasonal "equinoctial gale," or hurricane, common at that time of year, would blow away the fever.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Instead, heavy rains in late September seemed to correlate with a higher rate of cases.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Residents next anticipated freezing temperatures at night, which they knew were associated with ending fall fevers, but not why this was so.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] By the first two weeks of October, which was the peak of the crisis, gloom pervaded the city.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Most churches had stopped holding services, and the post office moved out of the area of the highest number of cases.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] The market days continued, and bakers continued to make and distribute bread.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Several members of the Mayor's Committee died.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] African-American nurses had also begun dying of the fever.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Carts took ill victims to Bush Hill and the dead to burial grounds.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Doctors also became ill and died, and fewer were available to care for patients.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Three of Rush's apprentices and his sister died; he was too sick to leave his house.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Such news cast doubts on Rush's methods, but none of those victims had submitted to his harsh treatment.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Those refugees from Saint-Domingue who thought they had immunity used the streets freely, but few other residents did.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Those who had not escaped the city tried to wait out the epidemic in their homes.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] When the Mayor's Committee took a quick census of the dead, they found that the majority of victims were poor people, who died in homes located in the alleys, behind the main streets where most of the business of city was conducted.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] On October 16, after temperatures cooled, a newspaper reported "the malignant fever has very considerably abated." Stores began to reopen October 25, many families returned, and the wharves were "once more enlivened" as a London-based ship arrived with goods.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] The Mayor's Committee advised people outside the city to wait another week or 10 days before returning.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] In the belief that the epidemic was related to bad air, the Committee published directions for cleaning houses which had been closed up, recommending that they be aired for several days with all windows and doors open.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] "Burning of nitre will correct the corrupt air which they may contain.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] But after some warm days, fever cases recurred.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Finally on November 13, stagecoaches resumed service to the north and south.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] A merchant reported the streets were "in an uproar and rendered the wharves impossible by reason of the vast quantities of wine, sugar, rum, coffee, cotton & c.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] An official register of deaths listed more than 5,000 people as dying from the 50,000 citizens of Philadelphia between August 1 and November 9, 1793, based on grave counts, so the total was probably higher.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] City officials, medical and religious leaders, and newspaper publishers reported the number and names of victims, based on the minutes of the Mayor's Committee.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] The appendix of the on-line edition of minutes lists the names of all the patients admitted to Bush Hill hospital, as well as the disposition of their cases.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Carey released his history of the epidemic just weeks after its end.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] He lists the names of the dead at the back of the book, which is one reason it was a bestseller.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Merchants worried more about Rush's theory that the fever arose from the filth of Philadelphia and was not imported from the West Indies.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] They did not want the port's reputation to suffer permanently.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Doctors used his treatments while rejecting his etiology of the disease.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Others deprecated his therapies, such as Dr.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Devèze, but agreed that the fever had local origins.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Devèze had arrived on the refugee ship from Saint-Domingue, which many accused of having carried the disease, but he thought it healthy.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] The doctors did not understand the origin or transmittal of the disease.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Kuhn advised drinking wine, "at first weaker wines, such as claret and Rhenish; if these cannot be had, Lisbon or Madeira diluted with rich lemonade.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] The patient is to be placed in a large empty tub, and two buckets full of water, of the temperature 75 or 80 degrees Fahrenheit's thermometer, according to the state of the atmosphere, are to be thrown on him." The water treatment was also advocated by Dr.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Edward Stevens, who in mid-September claimed it had cured Alexander Hamilton, Secretary of the Treasury, of the fever.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Rush searched the medical literature for other approaches.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Benjamin Franklin had given him letters sent by Dr.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] John Mitchell, related to treating patients during a 1741 yellow fever outbreak in Virginia.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] (Franklin never published the letters.) Mitchell noted that the stomach and intestines filled with blood and that these organs had to be emptied at all costs.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] "On this account," Mitchell argued, "an ill-timed scrupulousness about the weakness of the body is of bad consequences in these urging circumstances....
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Since the demand for his services was so great, he had his assistants make as many of his powders in pill form as they could.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] On September 10, he published a guide to treating the fever: "Dr.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Rush's Directions for Curing and Treating the Yellow Fever", outlining a regimen of self-medication.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Then after the "bowels are thoroughly cleaned," it was proper to take 8 to 10 ounces of blood from the arm if, after purging, the pulse was full or tense.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] To keep the body open he recommended more calomel or small doses of cream of tartar or other salts.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] If the pulse was weak and low, he recommended camomile or snakeroot as a stimulant, and blisters or blankets soaked in hot vinegar wrapped around the lower limbs.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Rush's therapy was generalized as "purge and bleed," and as long as the patient remained debilitated, Rush urged further purging and bleeding.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Not a few of his patients became comatose.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] The calomel in his pills soon brought on a state of constant salivation, which Rush urged patients to attain to assure a cure.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] A characteristic sign of death was black vomit, which salivation seemed to ward off.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Since he urged purging at the first sign of fever, other doctors began seeing patients who were in severe abdominal distress.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Autopsies after their death revealed stomachs destroyed by such purges.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Unlike other doctors, Devèze did not offer advice in the newspapers during the epidemic.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] He later discussed treatment in his memoir, which included 18 case studies and descriptions of several autopsies.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] While he deprecated Rush's harsh purgatives and "heroic" bleeding, he moderately bled patients and also used medicines to evacuate the bowels.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Like Rush, he thought poisons had to be "abstracted" in severely debilitated patients.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Instead of purges, he used blisters to raise welts on the skin.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] He preferred to apply heat, using hot bricks on hands or feet.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] He strongly discounted the traditional treatment for severe fevers, which was to wrap patients in blankets, give them camomile tea or Madeira, and try to bring on sweats.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] He preferred "acidulated" water to the use of Peruvian bark as many patients found the bark distasteful.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] He thought the use of opium very helpful.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] The governor created a middle path: he ordered the city to be kept clean and the port policed to prevent infected ships, or those from the Caribbean, from docking until they had gone through a period of quarantine.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] The city suffered additional yellow fever epidemics in 1797, 1798, and 1799, which kept the origin and treatment controversies alive.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Some of the city's clergy suggested the epidemic was a judgment from God.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Led by the Quakers, the religious community petitioned the state legislature to prohibit theatrical presentations in the state.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Such entertainment had been banned during the Revolution and had only recently been authorized.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] After an extensive debate in the newspapers, the State Assembly denied the petition.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] The recurrences of yellow fever kept discussions about causes, treatment and prevention going until the end of the decade.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Other major ports also had epidemics, beginning with Baltimore in 1794, New York in 1795 and 1798, and Wilmington and Boston in 1798, making yellow fever a national crisis.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] New York doctors finally admitted that they had had an outbreak of yellow fever in 1791 that killed more than 100 people.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] All the cities that suffered epidemics continued to grow rapidly.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] During the epidemic of 1798, Benjamin Rush commuted daily from a house just outside the city, near what is now 15th and Columbia streets, to the new city fever hospital, where as chief doctor he treated fever victims.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] American doctors did not identify the vector of yellow fever until the late 19th century.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] In 1881 Carlos Finlay, a Cuban doctor, argued that mosquito bites caused yellow fever; he credited Rush's published account of the 1793 epidemic for giving him the idea.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] In the first week of September 1793, Dr.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] William Currie published a description of the epidemic and an account of its progress during August.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Carey had an account of the epidemic for sale in the third week of October, before the epidemic had ended.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] The Allen and Jones published their own account rebutting Carey's attacks; by that time Carey had already published the fourth edition of his popular pamphlet.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Allen and Jones note that some blacks had worked for free, that they had died at the same rate as whites from the epidemic, and that some whites had also overcharged for their services.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Currie's work was the first of several medical accounts published within a year of the epidemic.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Rush published an account more than 300 pages long.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Devèze and Nassy published shorter accounts.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Clergymen also published accounts; the most notable was by the Lutheran minister J.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] In March 1794, the Mayor's Committee published its minutes.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] The rapid succession of other yellow fever epidemics in Philadelphia and elsewhere in the northeastern United States inspired many accounts of the efforts to contain, control and cope with the disease.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Rush wrote accounts of the 1797, 1798, and 1799 epidemics in Philadelphia.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] He revised his account of the 1793 epidemic to eliminate reference to the disease being contagious.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] In 1798 he was appointed as the chief doctor at the fever hospital.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] The mortality rate that year was roughly the same as it had been at Bush Hill in 1793, despite radical differences between the therapies used.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Noah Webster, a notable New York newspaper publisher, joined two doctors in publishing the *Medical Repository,* a magazine that collected accounts of fever epidemics throughout the nation.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Webster used this data in his 1798 book, suggesting that the nation was being subjected to a widespread "epidemic constitution" in the atmosphere that might last 50 years and make deadly epidemics almost certain.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Mortality was especially great in Philadelphia.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] This fact, along with the spread of the disease between Boston and Charleston between 1793 and 1802, made yellow fever a national crisis.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] General 20th-century US histories, such as the 10-volume *Great Epochs in American History,* published in 1912, use short excerpts from Carey's account.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] The first history of the epidemic to draw on more primary sources was J.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] While Powell did not write a scholarly history of the epidemic, his work reviews its historical importance.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Since the mid-20th century, scholars have studied aspects of the epidemic.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] For example, Martin Pernick's "Politics, Parties, and Pestilence: Epidemic Yellow Fever in Philadelphia and the Rise of the First Party System," develops statistical evidence to show that Republican doctors generally used Rush's therapies, and Federalist doctors used Kuhn's.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] Scholars marked the 200th anniversary of the epidemic with the publication of papers on various aspects of the epidemic.
[src:philadelphia/1793-philadelphia-yellow-fever-epidemic] A 2004 paper in the *Bulletin of the History of Medicine* examines Rush's use of bleeding.
[src:philadelphia/1800-united-states-census] The **1800 United States census** was the second census conducted in the United States.
[src:philadelphia/1800-united-states-census] It showed that 5,308,483 people were living in the United States, of whom 893,602 were slaves.
[src:philadelphia/1800-united-states-census] The 1800 census included the new District of Columbia.
[src:philadelphia/1800-united-states-census] The census for the following states were lost: Georgia, Kentucky, New Jersey, Tennessee, and Virginia.
[src:philadelphia/1800-united-states-census] In comparison to the 1790 census, the 1800 census gathered additional information.
[src:philadelphia/1800-united-states-census] The census was published in December 1801 and cost $66,109.04.
[src:philadelphia/1800-united-states-census] This census is one of the several for which some of the original data are no longer available.
[src:philadelphia/1800-united-states-census] Original census returns for Georgia, Kentucky, Mississippi, New Jersey, Tennessee, and Virginia were lost over the years.
[src:philadelphia/1800-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1800 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:philadelphia/1810-united-states-census] The **1810 United States census** was the third census conducted in the United States.
[src:philadelphia/1810-united-states-census] It showed that 7,239,881 people were living in the United States, of whom 1,191,362 were slaves.
[src:philadelphia/1810-united-states-census] The 1810 census included one new state: Ohio.
[src:philadelphia/1810-united-states-census] The original census returns for the District of Columbia, Georgia, Mississippi, New Jersey, and Ohio were lost or destroyed over the years.
[src:philadelphia/1810-united-states-census] Most of Tennessee's original forms were also lost, other than Grainger and Rutherford counties.
[src:philadelphia/1810-united-states-census] This was the last census with Virginia ranked as the most populous state.
[src:philadelphia/1810-united-states-census] Census taking was not yet an exact science.
[src:philadelphia/1810-united-states-census] Before 1830, enumerators lacked pre-printed forms, and some drew up their own, resulting in pages without headings.
[src:philadelphia/1810-united-states-census] Some enumerators did not tally their results.
[src:philadelphia/1810-united-states-census] As a result, census records for many towns before 1830 are idiosyncratic.
[src:philadelphia/1810-united-states-census] This is not to suggest that they are less reliable than subsequent censuses, but that they may require more work on the part of the researcher.
[src:philadelphia/1810-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1810 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:philadelphia/1820-united-states-census] The **1820 United States census** was the fourth census conducted in the United States.
[src:philadelphia/1820-united-states-census] The 1820 census included six new states: Louisiana, Indiana, Mississippi, Illinois, Alabama and Maine.
[src:philadelphia/1820-united-states-census] There has been a district wide loss of 1820 census records for Arkansas Territory, Missouri Territory, and New Jersey.
[src:philadelphia/1820-united-states-census] The total population was determined to be 9,638,453, of which 1,538,022 were slaves.
[src:philadelphia/1820-united-states-census] The center of population was about 120 miles (193 km) west-northwest of Washington in Hardy County, Virginia (now in West Virginia).
[src:philadelphia/1820-united-states-census] This was the first census in which any states recorded a population of over one million—New York, Virginia, and Pennsylvania—as well as the first in which a city recorded a population of over 100,000—New York.
[src:philadelphia/1820-united-states-census] Also, in this census and the 14 subsequent ones, New York was the most populous state until being superseded by California in the 1970 census.
[src:philadelphia/1820-united-states-census] The 1820 census contains a great deal more information than previous censuses.
[src:philadelphia/1820-united-states-census] Several of these columns were for special counts, and not to be included in the aggregate total.
[src:philadelphia/1820-united-states-census] Doing so would have resulted in counting some individuals twice.
[src:philadelphia/1820-united-states-census] Census takers were asked to use double lines, red ink or some other method of distinguishing these columns so that double counting would not occur.
[src:philadelphia/1820-united-states-census] For example, the count of free white males between 16 and 18 was a special count, because these individuals were also supposed to be tabulated in the column for free white males of age 16 and under 26.
[src:philadelphia/1820-united-states-census] The other special counts were foreigners not naturalized, persons engaged in agriculture, persons engaged in commerce, and persons engaged in manufacture.
[src:philadelphia/1820-united-states-census] Census takers were also instructed to count each individual in only one of the occupational columns.
[src:philadelphia/1820-united-states-census] For example, if an individual was engaged in agriculture, commerce, and manufacture, the census taker had to judge which one the individual was primarily engaged in.
[src:philadelphia/1820-united-states-census] Before 1830, enumerators lacked pre-printed forms, and drew up their own, sometimes resulting in pages without headings, line tallies, or column totals.
[src:philadelphia/1830-united-states-census] The **1830 United States census**, the fifth census undertaken in the United States, was conducted on June 1, 1830.
[src:philadelphia/1830-united-states-census] The only loss of census records for 1830 involved some countywide losses in Massachusetts, Maryland, and Mississippi.
[src:philadelphia/1830-united-states-census] It determined the population of the 24 states to be 12,866,020, of which 2,009,043 were slaves.
[src:philadelphia/1830-united-states-census] The center of population was about 170 miles (274 km) west of Washington, D.C. in present-day Grant County, West Virginia.
[src:philadelphia/1830-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a city—New York—recorded a population of over 200,000.
[src:philadelphia/1830-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1830 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:philadelphia/1835-philadelphia-general-strike] The **1835 Philadelphia general strike** took place in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.
[src:philadelphia/1835-philadelphia-general-strike] It was the first general strike in North America and involved some 20,000 workers who struck for a ten-hour workday and increased wages.
[src:philadelphia/1835-philadelphia-general-strike] The strike ended in workers successfully negotiating for and securing both.
[src:philadelphia/1835-philadelphia-general-strike] For some trades this worked out to a manageable average over the course of a year, but for the construction trades in particular, a business marked by heavy unemployment during the winter months owing to the weather, this state of affairs was regarded as an intolerable burden.
[src:philadelphia/1835-philadelphia-general-strike] As a result, the idea emerged that the length of the work day should be fixed by time rather than the rise and fall of the sun, and agitation for a ten-hour day began.
[src:philadelphia/1835-philadelphia-general-strike] During the 1820s and 1830s, a number of strikes were commenced to shorten the work day.
[src:philadelphia/1835-philadelphia-general-strike] In June 1827 some 600 Philadelphia journeymen carpenters—that is, the wage laborers employed by master carpenters—went on strike for the citywide establishment of the ten-hour day.
[src:philadelphia/1835-philadelphia-general-strike] Carpenters in Boston, Massachusetts similarly struck for a ten-hour workday in 1825 and 1832.
[src:philadelphia/1835-philadelphia-general-strike] However, the strikes were unsuccessful at shortening the work day.
[src:philadelphia/1835-philadelphia-general-strike] In 1835 Boston carpenters went on strike again for a ten-hour workday and were soon joined by masons and stone-cutters.
[src:philadelphia/1835-philadelphia-general-strike] The strikers chose Seth Luther and two other workers as leaders, and they issued a circular stating their demands.
[src:philadelphia/1835-philadelphia-general-strike] The circular read in part "We have been too long subjected to the odious, cruel, unjust and tyrannical system which compels the operative mechanic to exhaust his physical and mental powers.
[src:philadelphia/1835-philadelphia-general-strike] During the strike, the Boston workers organized a travelling committee and requested the assistance of workers in other cities.
[src:philadelphia/1835-philadelphia-general-strike] The Boston circular was well received by workers throughout the country.
[src:philadelphia/1835-philadelphia-general-strike] Although the Boston strike was eventually defeated, the circular was pivotal in motivating workers in Philadelphia to organize their own strike that year for a ten-hour workday.
[src:philadelphia/1835-philadelphia-general-strike] Influenced by events in Boston, unskilled Irish workers on the Schuylkill River coal wharves the same year went on strike for a ten-hour day.
[src:philadelphia/1835-philadelphia-general-strike] Three hundred workers marched on the coal wharves.
[src:philadelphia/1835-philadelphia-general-strike] They were led by a worker with a sword who threatened death to anyone who crossed the picket line and unloaded coal from the 75 vessels waiting in the water.
[src:philadelphia/1835-philadelphia-general-strike] The coal heavers were soon joined by workers from many other trades, including leather dressers, printers, carpenters, bricklayers, masons, house painters, bakers, and city employees.
[src:philadelphia/1835-philadelphia-general-strike] On June 6, a mass meeting of workers, lawyers, doctors, and a few businessmen, was held in the State House courtyard.
[src:philadelphia/1835-philadelphia-general-strike] The meeting unanimously adopted a set of resolutions giving full support to the workers' demand for wage increases and a shorter workday, as well as increased wages for women workers and a boycott of any coal merchant who worked his men more than ten hours.
[src:philadelphia/1835-philadelphia-general-strike] The strike quickly came to a close after city public works employees joined the action.
[src:philadelphia/1835-philadelphia-general-strike] The news of the strikers' success spread to other cities and was given large coverage.
[src:philadelphia/1835-philadelphia-general-strike] Strikes for the ten-hour day hit towns such as New Brunswick and Paterson, New Jersey, Batavia and Seneca Falls, New York, Hartford, Connecticut, and Salem, Massachusetts.
[src:philadelphia/1835-philadelphia-general-strike] By the end of 1835, the ten-hour day had become the standard for most city laborers who worked by the day with the exception of workers in Boston.
[src:philadelphia/1835-philadelphia-general-strike] Subsequently, the ten-hour day became an integral part of the labor movement in Europe.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Philadelphia was founded in 1682 by William Penn, an English Quaker and advocate of religious freedom, and served as the capital of the colonial era Province of Pennsylvania.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] It then played a vital role during the American Revolution and Revolutionary War.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] During the Revolutionary War's Philadelphia campaign, the city fell to the British Army, which occupied Philadelphia for nine months from September 1777 to June 1778.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Following the end of the Revolutionary War, the U.S.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Constitution was ratified at the Philadelphia Convention.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Philadelphia remained the nation's largest city until 1790, and it served as the nation's first capital from May 10, 1775, until December 12, 1776, and on four subsequent occasions until 1800, when construction of the new national capital in Washington, D.C. was completed.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] With 17 four-year universities and colleges in the city, Philadelphia is one of the nation's leading centers for higher education and academic research.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The city hosts more outdoor sculptures and murals than any other city in the nation.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Fairmount Park, when combined with adjacent Wissahickon Valley Park in the same watershed, has an area of 2,052 acres (830 ha), representing one of the nation's largest urban parks and the world's 55th largest.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] With five professional sports teams and one of the nation's most loyal and passionate fan bases, Philadelphia is often ranked as the nation's best city for professional sports fans.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The city has a culturally and philanthropically active LGBTQ+ community.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Philadelphia also has played an influential historic and ongoing role in the development and evolution of American music, especially R&B, soul, and rock.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] As of 2023, the Philadelphia metropolitan area had a gross metropolitan product of US$557.6 billion and is home to 13 *Fortune* 500 corporate headquarters.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Metropolitan Philadelphia ranks as one of the nation's Big Five venture capital hubs, facilitated by its proximity to both the financial ecosystems of New York City and the regulatory environment of Washington, D.C.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Metropolitan Philadelphia is also a biotechnology hub and has garnered the nickname "Cellicon Valley" for its central role in the development of immunotherapies to treat different cancers.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The Philadelphia Stock Exchange, owned by Nasdaq since 2008, is the nation's oldest stock exchange and a global leader in options trading.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] 30th Street Station, the city's primary rail station, is the third-busiest Amtrak hub in the nation with over 4.1 million passengers in 2023.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The city's multimodal transportation and logistics infrastructure includes Philadelphia International Airport, the PhilaPort seaport, and Interstate 95, a primary component of the north–south highway system along the U.S.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Philadelphia is a city of many firsts, including the nation's first library (1731), hospital (1751), medical school (1765), national capital (1774), university (by some accounts) (1779), central bank (1781), stock exchange (1790), zoo (1874), and business school (1881).
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Philadelphia contains 67 National Historic Landmarks, including Independence Hall.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] From the city's 17th century founding through the present, Philadelphia has been the birthplace of or home to many prominent and influential Americans.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Before the arrival of Europeans in the early 17th century, the Lenape, an Indian tribe also known as the Delaware Indians, lived in the village of Shackamaxon in present-day Philadelphia and the surrounding area.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The Lenape historically lived along the Delaware River watershed, western Long Island, and the Lower Hudson Valley.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Most Lenape were pushed out of the region during the 18th century as the original Thirteen Colonies expanded, which was further exacerbated by losses from intertribal conflicts.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Lenape communities were also weakened by newly introduced diseases, mainly smallpox, and conflicts with Europeans.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The Iroquois occasionally fought the Lenape.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Surviving Lenape moved west into the upper Ohio River basin.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Following the American Revolutionary War and the subsequent establishment of the United States, the Lenape began moving further west.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] In the 1860s, the U.S. federal government sent most remaining Lenape in the eastern United States to the Indian Territory in present-day Oklahoma and surrounding territories as part of the Indian removal policy.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Europeans first entered Philadelphia and the surrounding Delaware Valley in the early 17th century.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The first settlements were founded by Dutch colonists, who built Fort Nassau on the Delaware River in 1623 in what is now Brooklawn, New Jersey.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The Dutch considered the entire Delaware River valley to be part of their New Netherland colony.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] In 1638, Swedish settlers led by renegade Dutch established the colony of New Sweden at Fort Christina, located in present-day Wilmington, Delaware, and quickly spread out in the valley.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] In 1644, New Sweden supported the Susquehannocks in their war against Maryland colonists.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] In 1648, the Dutch built Fort Beversreede on the west bank of the Delaware, south of the Schuylkill River near the present-day Eastwick section of Philadelphia, to reassert their dominion over the area.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The Swedes responded by building Fort Nya Korsholm, or New Korsholm, named after a town in Finland with a Swedish majority.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] In 1655, a Dutch military campaign led by New Netherland Director-General Peter Stuyvesant took control of the Swedish colony, ending its claim to independence.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The Swedish and Finnish settlers continued to have their own militia, religion, and court, and to enjoy substantial autonomy under the Dutch.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] An English fleet captured the New Netherland colony in 1664, though the situation did not change substantially until 1682, when the area was included in William Penn's charter for Pennsylvania.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] In 1681, in partial repayment of a debt, Charles II of England granted Penn a charter for what would become the Pennsylvania colony.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Despite the royal charter, Penn bought the land from the local Lenape in an effort to establish good terms with the Native Americans and ensure peace for the colony.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Penn made a treaty of friendship with Lenape chief Tammany under an elm tree at Shackamaxon, in what is now the city's Fishtown neighborhood.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Penn named the city Philadelphia, which is Greek for 'brotherly love', derived from the Ancient Greek terms φίλος *phílos* ('beloved, dear') and ἀδελφός *adelphós* ('brother, brotherly').
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] There were a number of cities named *Philadelphia* (Φιλαδέλφεια) in the Eastern Mediterranean during the Greek and Roman periods, including modern Alaşehir, mentioned as the site of an early Christian congregation in the Book of Revelation.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] As a Quaker, Penn had experienced religious persecution and wanted his colony to be a place where anyone could worship freely.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] This tolerance, which exceeded that of other colonies, led to better relations with the local native tribes and fostered Philadelphia's rapid growth into America's most important city.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Penn planned a city on the Delaware River to serve as a port and place for government.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Hoping that Philadelphia would become more like an English rural town instead of a city, Penn laid out roads on a grid plan to keep houses and businesses spread far apart with areas for gardens and orchards.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The city's inhabitants did not follow Penn's plans, however, and instead crowded the present-day Port of Philadelphia on the Delaware River and subdivided and resold their lots.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Before Penn left Philadelphia for the final time, he issued the Charter of 1701 establishing it as a city.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Though poor at first, Philadelphia became an important trading center with tolerable living conditions by the 1750s.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Benjamin Franklin, a leading citizen, helped improve city services and founded new ones that were among the first in the nation, including a fire company, library, and hospital.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] These societies developed and financed new industries that attracted skilled and knowledgeable immigrants from Europe.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Philadelphia's importance and central location in the colonies made it a natural center for America's revolutionaries.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] By the 1750s, Philadelphia surpassed Boston as the largest city and busiest port in British America, and the second-largest city in the entire British Empire after London.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] In 1774, as resentment of the British government's policies towards the colonies and support for independence began burgeoning in the colonies, Philadelphia hosted the First Continental Congress at Carpenters' Hall, and 12 of the original 13 colonies sent delegates to the Congress.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] From 1775 to 1781, Philadelphia hosted the Second Continental Congress, whose 56 delegates unanimously adopted the Declaration of Independence inside what was then called Pennsylvania State House and was later renamed Independence Hall.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Since the Declaration's July 4, 1776, adoption, its signing has been cited globally and repeatedly by various peoples of the world seeking independence and liberty.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] It also has been, since its adoption, the basis for annual celebration by Americans; in 1938, this celebration of the Declaration was formalized as Independence Day, one of only eleven designated U.S. federal holidays.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] After George Washington's defeat at the Battle of Brandywine in Chadds Ford Township, on September 11, 1777, during the Philadelphia campaign, the revolutionary capital of Philadelphia was defenseless, and the city prepared for what was perceived to be an inevitable British attack.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Because bells could easily be recast into munitions, the Liberty Bell, then known as the Pennsylvania State Bell, and bells from two Philadelphia churches, Christ Church and St.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Peter's Church, were hastily taken down and transported by heavily guarded wagon train out of the city.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The Liberty Bell was taken to Zion German Reformed Church in Northampton Town, which is present-day Allentown, where it was hidden under the church's floor boards for nine months from September 1777 until departure of British forces from Philadelphia in June 1778.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Two Revolutionary War battles, the Siege of Fort Mifflin, fought between September 26 and November 16, 1777, and the Battle of Germantown, fought on October 4, 1777, took place within Philadelphia's city limits.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] In Philadelphia, the Second Continental Congress adopted the Articles of Confederation on November 15, 1777.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Independence Hall in Philadelphia was the meeting place for the Constitutional Convention, which ratified the Constitution on September 17, 1787, which is now the longest-standing codified national constitution.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Philadelphia served as capital of the United States on five separate occasions between 1776 and 1800—in sum, most of the colonial and early post-colonial period, including the decade before 1800, when Washington, D.C., became the national capital.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] In 1793, the largest yellow fever epidemic in U.S. history killed about 4,000 to 5,000 people in Philadelphia, or about ten percent of the city's population at the time.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The state capital was moved from Philadelphia to Lancaster in 1799, then ultimately to Harrisburg in 1812.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Philadelphia remained the nation's largest city until the late 18th century.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] It also was the nation's financial and cultural center until ultimately being eclipsed in total population by New York City in 1790.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] In 1816, the city's free Black community founded the African Methodist Episcopal Church, the first independent Black denomination in the country, and the first Black Episcopal Church.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The free Black community also established many schools for its children with the help of Quakers.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Large-scale construction projects for new roads, canals, and railroads made Philadelphia the first major industrial city in the United States.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Throughout the 19th century, Philadelphia hosted a variety of industries and businesses; the largest was the textile industry.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Major corporations in the 19th and early 20th centuries included the Baldwin Locomotive Works, William Cramp & Sons Shipbuilding Company, and the Pennsylvania Railroad.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Established in 1870, the Philadelphia Conveyancers' Association was chartered by the state in 1871.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Centennial in 1876, the city's industry was celebrated in the Centennial Exposition, the first official World's fair in the U.S.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Immigrants, mostly from Ireland and Germany, settled in Philadelphia and the surrounding districts.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] These immigrants were largely responsible for the first general strike in North America in 1835, in which workers in the city won the ten-hour workday.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The city was a destination for thousands of Irish immigrants fleeing the Great Famine in the 1840s; housing for them was developed south of South Street and later occupied by succeeding immigrants.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] They established a network of Catholic churches and schools and dominated the Catholic clergy for decades.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Anti-Irish, anti-Catholic nativist riots erupted in Philadelphia in 1844.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The rise in population of the surrounding districts helped lead to the Act of Consolidation of 1854, which extended the city limits from the 2 square miles (5.2 km2) of Center City to the roughly 134 square miles (350 km2) of Philadelphia County.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] In the latter half of the 19th century and leading into the 20th century, immigrants from Russia, Eastern Europe, and Italy, and African Americans from the southern U.S. settled in the city.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Philadelphia was represented by the Washington Grays in the American Civil War.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The African-American population of Philadelphia increased from 31,699 to 219,559 between 1880 and 1930, largely stemming from the Great Migration from the South.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] By the 20th century, Philadelphia had an entrenched Republican political machine and a complacent population.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] In 1910, a general strike shut down the entire city.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] In 1917, following outrage over the election-year murder of a Philadelphia police officer, the City Council shrank from two houses to just one.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] In July 1919, Philadelphia was one of more than 36 industrial cities nationally to suffer a race riot during Red Summer in post-World War I unrest as recent immigrants competed with Black residents for jobs.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] In the 1920s, the public flouting of Prohibition laws, organized crime, mob violence, and corrupt police involvement in illegal activities led to the appointment of Brig.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Marine Corps as the city's director of public safety, but political pressure still prevented long-term success in fighting crime and corruption.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] In 1940, non-Hispanic whites constituted 86.8% of the city's population.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] In 1950, the population peaked at more than two million residents, then began to decline with the restructuring of industry that led to the loss of many middle-class union jobs.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] In addition, suburbanization enticed many affluent residents to depart the city for its outlying railroad commuting towns and newer housing.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The resulting reduction in Philadelphia's tax base and the resources of local government caused the city to struggle through a long period of adjustment, and it approached bankruptcy by the late 1980s.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] In 1985, the Philadelphia Police Department, utilizing a Pennsylvania State Police helicopter, bombed the Cobbs Creek neighborhood to execute arrest warrants on MOVE members, a Black liberation movement.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The incident killed 11 people, destroyed 61 homes, and displaced 250 residents, marking one of the only times a US city intentionally bombed its own civilians.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Revitalization and gentrification of neighborhoods began in the late 1970s and continues into the 21st century with much of the development occurring in the Center City and University City neighborhoods.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] But this expanded a shortage of affordable housing in the city.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] After many manufacturers and businesses left Philadelphia or shut down, the city started attracting service businesses and began to market itself more aggressively as a tourist destination.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Contemporary glass-and-granite skyscrapers were built in Center City beginning in the 1980s.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Historic areas such as Old City and Society Hill were renovated during the reformist mayoral era of the 1950s through the 1980s, making both areas among the most desirable Center City neighborhoods.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Immigrants from around the world began to enter the U.S. through Philadelphia as their gateway, leading to a reversal of the city's population decline between 1950 and 2000, during which it lost about 25 percent of its residents.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Philadelphia eventually began experiencing a growth in its population in 2007, which continued with incremental annual increases through the present.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] A migration pattern has been established from New York City to Philadelphia by residents opting for a large city with relative proximity and a lower cost of living.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Philadelphia's geographic center is about 40° 0′ 34″ north latitude and 75° 8′ 0″ west longitude.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The 40th parallel north passes through neighborhoods in Northeast Philadelphia, North Philadelphia, and West Philadelphia including Fairmount Park.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Natural bodies of water include the Delaware and Schuylkill rivers, lakes in Franklin Delano Roosevelt Park, and Cobbs, Wissahickon, and Pennypack creeks.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The largest artificial body of water is East Park Reservoir in Fairmount Park.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The lowest point is sea level and the highest point is in Chestnut Hill, about 446 feet (136 m) above sea level on Summit Street near the intersection of Germantown Avenue and Bethlehem Pike at: 40.07815 N, 75.20747 W.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Philadelphia is located on the Atlantic Seaboard Fall Line that separates the Atlantic Plain from the Piedmont.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The Schuylkill River's rapids at East Falls were inundated by completion of the dam at Fairmount Water Works.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The city is bordered by six adjacent counties: Montgomery to the northwest; Bucks to the north and northeast; Burlington County, New Jersey to the east; Camden County, New Jersey to the southeast; Gloucester County, New Jersey to the south; and Delaware County to the southwest.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Philadelphia was created in the 17th century, following the plan by William Penn's surveyor Thomas Holme.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Center City is structured with long, straight streets running nearly due east–west and north–south, forming a grid pattern between the Delaware and Schuylkill rivers that is aligned with their courses.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The original city plan was designed to allow for easy travel and to keep residences separated by open space that would help prevent the spread of fire.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] In keeping with the idea of a "Greene Countrie Towne", and inspired by the many types of trees that grew in the region, Penn named many of the east–west streets for local trees.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Penn planned the creation of five public parks in the city which were renamed in 1824.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Centre Square was renamed Penn Square; Northeast Square was renamed Franklin Square; Southeast Square was renamed Washington Square; Southwest Square was renamed Rittenhouse Square; and Northwest Square was renamed Logan Circle/Square.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Center City had an estimated 183,240 residents as of 2015, making it the second-most populated downtown area in the United States after Midtown Manhattan in New York City.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Philadelphia's neighborhoods are divided into six large sections that surround Center City: North Philadelphia, Northeast Philadelphia, South Philadelphia, Southwest Philadelphia, West Philadelphia, and Northwest Philadelphia.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The city's geographic boundaries have been largely unchanged since these neighborhoods were consolidated in 1854.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] However, each of these large areas contains numerous neighborhoods, some of whose boundaries derive from the boroughs, townships, and other communities that constituted Pennsylvania County before their inclusion within the city.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The City Planning Commission, tasked with guiding growth and development of the city, has divided the city into 18 planning districts as part of the Philadelphia2035 physical development plan.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Much of the city's 1980 zoning code was overhauled from 2007 to 2012 as part of a joint effort between former mayors John F.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The zoning changes were intended to rectify incorrect zoning maps to facilitate future community development, as the city forecasts an additional 100,000 residents and 40,000 jobs will be added by 2035.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The Philadelphia Housing Authority (PHA) is the largest landlord in Pennsylvania.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Established in 1937, the PHA is the nation's fourth-largest housing authority, serving about 81,000 people with affordable housing, while employing 1,400 on a budget of $371 million.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The Philadelphia Parking Authority is responsible for ensuring adequate parking for city residents, businesses, and visitors.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Philadelphia's architectural history dates back to colonial times and includes a wide range of styles.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The earliest structures were constructed with logs, but brick structures were common by 1700.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] During the 18th century, the cityscape was dominated by Georgian architecture, including Independence Hall and Christ Church.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] In the first decades of the 19th century, Federal and Greek Revival architecture were the dominant styles produced by Philadelphia architects such as Benjamin Latrobe, William Strickland, John Haviland, John Notman, Thomas Walter, and Samuel Sloan.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Frank Furness is considered Philadelphia's greatest architect of the second half of the 19th century.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] His contemporaries included John McArthur Jr., Addison Hutton, Wilson Eyre, the Wilson Brothers, and Horace Trumbauer.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] In 1871, construction began on the Second Empire-style Philadelphia City Hall.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The Philadelphia Historical Commission was created in 1955 to preserve the cultural and architectural history of the city.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The commission maintains the Philadelphia Register of Historic Places, adding historic buildings, structures, sites, objects and districts as it sees fit.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] In 1932, Philadelphia became home to the first modern International Style skyscraper in the United States, the PSFS Building, designed by George Howe and William Lescaze.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The 548 ft (167 m) City Hall remained the tallest building in the city until 1987 when One Liberty Place was completed.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Numerous glass and granite skyscrapers were built in Center City beginning in the late 1980s.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] In 2007, the Comcast Center surpassed One Liberty Place to become the city's tallest building.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The Comcast Technology Center was completed in 2018, reaching a height of 1,121 ft (342 m), as the tallest building in the United States outside of Manhattan and Chicago.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] For much of Philadelphia's history, the typical home has been the row house.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The row house was introduced to the United States via Philadelphia in the early 19th century and, for a time, row houses built elsewhere in the United States were known as "Philadelphia rows".
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] A variety of row houses are found throughout the city, from Federal-style continuous blocks in Old City and Society Hill to Victorian-style homes in North Philadelphia to twin row houses in West Philadelphia.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] While newer homes have been built recently, much of the housing dates to the 18th, 19th, and early 20th centuries, which has created problems such as urban decay and vacant lots.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Some neighborhoods, including Northern Liberties and Society Hill, have been rehabilitated through gentrification.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] As of 2014, the city's total park space, including municipal, state, and federal parks in the city, amounts to 11,211 acres (17.5 sq mi).
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Philadelphia's largest park is Fairmount Park, which includes the Philadelphia Zoo and encompasses 2,052 acres (3.2 sq mi) of the total parkland.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Fairmount Park's adjacent Wissahickon Valley Park contains 2,042 acres (3.2 sq mi).
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Fairmount Park, when combined with Wissahickon Valley Park, is one of the largest contiguous urban park areas in the U.S.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The two parks, along with the Colonial Revival, Georgian and Federal-style mansions in them, have been listed as one entity on the National Register of Historic Places since 1972.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Within the Köppen climate classification, Philadelphia falls under the northern periphery of the humid subtropical climate zone (Köppen *Cfa*), while under the Trewartha climate classification, the city is classified as a maritime climate (*Do*) bordered to the north by the continental (*Dc*) zone.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Fall and spring are generally mild, and winter is moderately cold.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The plant life hardiness zones are 7a and 7b, reflecting an average annual extreme minimum temperature between 0 and 10 °F (−18 and −12 °C).
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Some winters have only light snow while others include major snowstorms.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The normal seasonal snowfall averages 22.4 in (57 cm), with rare snowfalls in November or April, and rarely any sustained snow cover.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Seasonal snowfall accumulation has ranged from trace amounts in 1972–73, to 78.7 inches (200 cm) in the winter of 2009–10.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The city's heaviest single-storm snowfall was 30.7 in (78 cm), which occurred in January 1996.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Precipitation is generally spread throughout the year, with eight to eleven wet days per month, at an average annual rate of 44.1 inches (1,120 mm), but historically ranging from 29.31 in (744 mm) in 1922 to 64.33 in (1,634 mm) in 2011.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The most rain recorded in one day occurred on July 28, 2013, when 8.02 in (204 mm) fell at Philadelphia International Airport.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Philadelphia has a moderately sunny climate with an average of 2,498 hours of sunshine annually.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The percentage of sunshine ranges from 47% in December to 61% in June, July, and August.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The January daily average temperature is 33.7 °F (0.9 °C).
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The temperature frequently rises to 50 °F (10 °C) during thaws.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Heat waves accompanied by high humidity and heat indices are frequent, with highs reaching or exceeding 90 °F (32 °C) on 30 days of the year.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The average window for freezing temperatures is November 6 to April 2, allowing a growing season of 217 days.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Early fall and late winter are generally dry, with February having the lowest average precipitation at 2.75 inches (70 mm).
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The dewpoint in the summer averages between 59.1 and 64.5 °F (15 and 18 °C).
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The highest recorded temperature was 106 °F (41 °C) on August 7, 1918.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Temperatures at or above 100 °F (38 °C) are not common, with the last occurrence of such a temperature being July 21, 2019.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The lowest officially recorded temperature was −11 °F (−24 °C) on February 9, 1934.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Temperatures at or below 0 °F (−18 °C) are rare, with the last such occurrence being January 19, 1994.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The record high dew point is 82 °F (28 °C) which occurred on July 15, 1995.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Philadelphia County received an ozone grade of F and a 24-hour particle pollution rating of D in the American Lung Association's 2017 State of the Air report, which analyzed data from 2013 to 2015.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The city was ranked 22nd for ozone, 20th for short-term particle pollution, and 11th for year-round particle pollution.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Five of the ten largest combined statistical areas (CSAs) were ranked higher for ozone: Los Angeles (1st), New York City (9th), Houston (12th), Dallas (13th), and San Jose, California (18th).
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Many smaller CSAs were also ranked higher for ozone, including Sacramento (8th), Las Vegas (10th), Denver (11th), El Paso (16th), and Salt Lake City (20th).
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Only two of those same ten CSAs, San Jose and Los Angeles, were ranked higher than Philadelphia for both year-round and short-term particle pollution.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] As of the 2020 U.S. census, there were 1,603,797 people residing in Philadelphia, representing a 1.2% increase from the 2019 census estimate.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The racial composition of the city was 39.3% Black alone (42.0% Black alone or in combination), 36.3% White alone (41.9% White alone or in combination), 8.7% Asian alone, 0.4% American Indian and Alaska Native alone, 8.7% some other race, and 6.9% multiracial.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] 14.9% of residents were Hispanic or Latino.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] 34.8% had a bachelor's degree or higher.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] 23.9% spoke a language other than English at home, the most common of which was Spanish (10.8%).
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] 15.0% of the population is foreign born, roughly half of whom are naturalized U.S. citizens.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The median household income was $52,889 and 22.8% of the population lived in poverty.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] 49.5% of the population drove alone to work, while 23.2% used public transit, 8.2% carpooled, 7.9% walked, and 7.0% worked from home.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] After the 1950 census, when a record high of 2,071,605 was recorded, the city's population began a long decline.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The population dropped to a low of 1,488,710 residents in 2006 before beginning to rise again.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Between 2006 and 2017, Philadelphia added 92,153 residents.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Census Bureau estimated that the racial composition of the city was 41.3% Black (non-Hispanic), 34.9% White (non-Hispanic), 14.1% Hispanic or Latino, 7.1% Asian, 0.4% Native American, 0.05% Pacific Islander, and 2.8% multiracial.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] In addition to the city's economic growth, the city's population has been fueled by foreign immigration.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Irish, Italian, German, Polish, English, Russian, Ukrainian, and French ancestries constitute the largest European ethnic groups in the city.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Philadelphia has the second-largest Irish and Italian populations in the United States after New York City.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] South Philadelphia remains one of the largest Italian neighborhoods in the country and is home to the Italian Market.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The Pennsport neighborhood and Gray's Ferry section of South Philadelphia, home to many Mummer clubs, are well known as Irish neighborhoods.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The Kensington, Port Richmond, and Fishtown neighborhoods have historically been heavily Irish and Polish.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Port Richmond is a center for the Polish-American community in Philadelphia, and it remains a common destination for Polish immigrants.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Northeast Philadelphia, although known for its Irish and Irish-American population, is home to a Jewish and Russian population.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Mount Airy in Northwest Philadelphia also contains a Jewish community.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Nearby Chestnut Hill is historically known as an Anglo-Saxon Protestant community.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Philadelphia's Black American population is the fourth-largest in the country after New York City, Chicago, and Houston.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] West Philadelphia and North Philadelphia are largely African-American neighborhoods, but many are leaving those areas in favor of the Northeast and Southwest sections of Philadelphia.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] A higher proportion of African-American Muslims reside in Philadelphia than most other major U.S. cities.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] West Philadelphia and Southwest Philadelphia are home to various Afro-Caribbean and African immigrant communities.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The Puerto Rican population in Philadelphia is the second-largest on the U.S. mainland after New York City, and the second-fastest growing after Orlando.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Eastern North Philadelphia, particularly Fairhill and surrounding areas to the north and east, has one of the highest concentrations of Puerto Ricans outside Puerto Rico, with many large swaths of blocks being close to 100% Puerto Rican.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Puerto Rican and Dominican populations reside in North Philadelphia and the Northeast, and Mexican and Central American populations exist in South Philadelphia.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] South American migrants were being transported by bus from Texas to Philadelphia beginning in 2022.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Philadelphia's Asian American population includes those of Chinese, Indians, Vietnamese, South Koreans, Filipinos, Cambodians, and Indonesians.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Over 35,000 Chinese Americans lived in the city in 2015, including a Fuzhounese population.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Center City hosts a Chinatown that is served by Chinatown bus lines with service to/from Chinatown, Manhattan.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Indians make up the second-largest Asian group in the city of Philadelphia, while making up the largest foreign-born population in the Philadelphia metropolitan area.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] A Korean community initially settled in the North Philadelphia neighborhood of Olney; however, the primary Koreatown has subsequently shifted further north, straddling the city's border with adjacent Cheltenham in Montgomery County and Cherry Hill in South Jersey.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] South Philadelphia is home to Vietnamese-Americans in Little Saigon and Cambodian-Americans in Cambodia Town, as well as Thai-American, Indonesian-American, and Chinese-American communities.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Philadelphia's Gay village near Washington Square is home to a concentration of gay and lesbian-friendly businesses, restaurants, and bars.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] In a 2014 study by the Pew Research Center, 68% of the population of the city identified themselves as Christian.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Approximately 41% of Christians in the city and area professed attendance at a variety of churches that could be considered Protestant, while 26% professed Catholic beliefs.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The Protestant Christian community in Philadelphia is dominated by mainline Protestant denominations including the Evangelical Lutheran Church in America, United Church of Christ, the Episcopal Church in the United States, Presbyterian Church (USA) and American Baptist Churches USA.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] One of the most prominent mainline Protestant jurisdictions is the Episcopal Diocese of Pennsylvania.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The African Methodist Episcopal Church was established in Philadelphia.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Historically, the city has strong connections to the Quakers, Unitarian Universalism, and the Ethical Culture movement, all of which continue to be represented in the city.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The Quaker Friends General Conference is based in Philadelphia.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Evangelical Protestants making up less than 15% of the population were also prevalent.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Evangelical Protestant bodies included the Anglican Church in North America, Lutheran Church—Missouri Synod, Presbyterian Church in America, and National Baptist Convention of America.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The Latin Church-based jurisdiction is headquartered in the city, and its see is the Cathedral Basilica of Saints Peter and Paul.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The Ukrainian Catholic jurisdiction is headquartered in Philadelphia, and is seated at the Cathedral of the Immaculate Conception.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Less than 1% of Philadelphia's Christians were Mormons.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The remainder of the Christian demographic is spread among smaller Protestant denominations and the Eastern and Oriental Orthodox among others.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The Diocese of Eastern Pennsylvania (Orthodox Church in America) and Greek Orthodox Archdiocese of America (Ecumenical Patriarchate) divide the Eastern Orthodox in Philadelphia.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The same study says that other religions collectively compose about 8% of the population, including Judaism, Hinduism, Islam, Buddhism, and Sikhism.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Philadelphia has the fifth-largest Muslim population among U.S. cities.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The remaining 24% claimed no religious affiliation.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] The Philadelphia metropolitan area's Jewish population was estimated at 206,000 in 2001, which was the sixth-largest in the U.S. at that time.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Jewish traders were operating in southeastern Pennsylvania long before William Penn.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Jews in Philadelphia took a prominent part in the War of Independence.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Although the majority of the early Jewish residents were of Portuguese or Spanish descent, some among them had emigrated from Germany and Poland.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] About the beginning of the 19th century, a number of Jews from the latter countries, finding the services of the Congregation Mickvé Israel unfamiliar to them, resolved to form a new congregation which would use the ritual to which they had been accustomed.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] African diasporic religions are practiced in some Latino and Hispanic and Caribbean communities in North and West Philadelphia.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] In total, 20.88% (293,544) of Philadelphia's population age 5 and older spoke a mother language other than English.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p01] Philadelphia is home to many food poverty programs, of which two of the largest are Philabundance which claims to feed 90000 people per week. and Share Food Program which claims to feed 1 million people per month.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Philadelphia's close geographical and transportation connections to other large metropolitan economies along the Eastern Seaboard of the United States have been cited as offering a significant competitive advantage for business creation and entrepreneurship.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The city is the center of economic activity in both Pennsylvania and the four-state Philadelphia metropolitan area.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Five Fortune 500 companies are based in the city.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] As of 2021, the Philadelphia metropolitan area is estimated to produce a gross metropolitan product (GMP) of US$479 billion, an increase from the $445 billion calculated by the Bureau of Economic Analysis for 2017, representing the ninth-largest U.S. metropolitan economy.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Philadelphia's economic sectors include financial services, health care, biotechnology, information technology, trade and transportation, manufacturing, oil refining, food processing, and tourism.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Metropolitan Philadelphia is one of the top five American venture capital hubs, credited to its proximity to New York City's financial and tech and biotechnology ecosystems.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Financial activities account for the largest economic sector of the metropolitan area, which is one of the largest health education and research centers in the United States.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The city's two largest employers are the federal and city governments.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Philadelphia's largest private employer is the University of Pennsylvania followed by Children's Hospital of Philadelphia.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The Philadelphia Stock Exchange, acquired by Nasdaq in 2007, is a global leader in options trading.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Other corporate headquarters in the city include Crown Holdings, and Brandywine Realty Trust.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The headquarters of Boeing Rotorcraft Systems and its main rotorcraft factory are in the Philadelphia suburb of Ridley Park; The Vanguard Group and the U.S. headquarters of Siemens Healthineers are headquartered in Malvern, Pennsylvania, a Philadelphia suburb.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Healthcare conglomerate AmerisourceBergen and the North American headquarters of furniture retailer IKEA are located in suburban Conshohocken, Pennsylvania.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Across the Delaware River in adjacent Camden County, New Jersey, Campbell Soup Company and Subaru USA are both headquartered in Camden, New Jersey, and TD Bank (USA) is headquartered in nearby suburban Cherry Hill, New Jersey.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Philadelphia is a hub for information technology and biotechnology.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Philadelphia and Pennsylvania are attracting new life sciences ventures.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] As of 2024, the Philadelphia metropolitan area ranks as one of the Big Five U.S. venture capital hubs, enabled by its proximity to both the entrepreneurial and financial ecosystems of New York City and to the federal regulatory environment of Washington, D.C.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Philadelphia's history attracts many tourists, with the Independence National Historical Park, which includes the Liberty Bell, Independence Hall, and other historic sites, received over 5 million visitors in 2016.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The city welcomed 42 million domestic tourists in 2016 who spent $6.8 billion, generating an estimated $11 billion in total economic impact in the city and surrounding four counties of Pennsylvania.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The annual Naked Bike Ride attracts participants from around the United States and internationally to Philadelphia.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The Port of Philadelphia, having experienced the highest percentage growth by tonnage loaded in 2017 among major U.S. seaports, has doubled its shipping capacity to accommodate super-sized post-Panamax shipping vessels since 2018.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Philadelphia's 30th Street Station is the third-busiest Amtrak rail hub, following Penn Station in Manhattan and Union Station in Washington, D.C., transporting over 4 million inter-city rail passengers annually.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Philadelphia is home to many national historical sites that relate to the founding of the United States.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Independence National Historical Park is the center of these historical landmarks and one of the country's 22 UNESCO World Heritage Sites.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Independence Hall, where the Declaration of Independence was signed, and the Liberty Bell is housed, are among the city's most popular attractions.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Other national historic sites include the homes of Edgar Allan Poe and Thaddeus Kosciuszko, and early government buildings, including the First and the Second Bank of the United States, Fort Mifflin, and the Gloria Dei (Old Swedes') Church.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Philadelphia alone has 67 National Historic Landmarks, the third most of any city in the country.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Philadelphia's major science museums include the Franklin Institute, which contains the Benjamin Franklin National Memorial, the Academy of Natural Sciences, the Mütter Museum, and the University of Pennsylvania Museum of Archaeology and Anthropology.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Philadelphia is home to the United States's first zoo and hospital, as well as Fairmount Park, one of America's oldest and largest urban parks, founded in 1855.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The city is home to important archival repositories, including the Library Company of Philadelphia, established in 1731 by Benjamin Franklin at 1314 Locust Street, and the Athenaeum of Philadelphia, founded in 1814.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The Presbyterian Historical Society is the country's oldest denominational historical society, organized in 1852.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The city is home to multiple art museums, including the Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts and the Rodin Museum, which holds the largest collection of work by Auguste Rodin outside France.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The city's largest art museum, the Philadelphia Museum of Art, is one of the largest art museums in the world.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The long flight of steps to the Art Museum's main entrance became famous after the film *Rocky* (1976).
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Areas such as South Street and the Old City section of the city have a vibrant night life.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The Avenue of the Arts in Center City contains many restaurants and theaters, such as the Kimmel Center for the Performing Arts, home of the Philadelphia Orchestra, and the Academy of Music, home of Opera Philadelphia and the Pennsylvania Ballet.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The Wilma Theatre and the Philadelphia Theatre Company at the Suzanne Roberts Theatre produce a variety of new plays.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Several blocks to the east are the Lantern Theater Company at St.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Stephens Episcopal Church; and the Walnut Street Theatre, a National Historic Landmark stated to be the oldest and most subscribed-to theatre in the English-speaking world, founded in 1809.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] In May 2019, the Walnut Street Theatre announced a major expansion to begin in 2020.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] New Freedom Theatre, Pennsylvania's oldest African-American theatre, is located on North Broad Street.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Philadelphia has more public art than any other American city.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] In 1872, the Association for Public Art, formerly the Fairmount Park Art Association, was created as the first private association in the United States dedicated to integrating public art and urban planning.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] In 1959, lobbying by the Artists Equity Association helped create the Percent for Art ordinance, the first for a U.S. city.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The program, which has funded more than 200 pieces of public art, is administered by Creative Philadelphia, the city's office of arts and culture.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The city has more murals than any other American city, due to the 1984 creation of the Department of Recreation's Mural Arts Program, which seeks to beautify neighborhoods and provide an outlet for graffiti artists.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The program has funded more than 2,800 murals by professional, staff and volunteer artists and educated more than 20,000 youth in underserved neighborhoods throughout Philadelphia.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The city is home to a number of art organizations, including the regional art advocacy nonprofit Philadelphia Tri-State Artists Equity, the Philadelphia Sketch Club, one of the country's oldest artists' clubs, and The Plastic Club, started by women excluded from the Sketch Club.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Many Old City art galleries stay open late on the First Friday event of each month.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The city is known for its hoagies, stromboli, roast pork sandwich, scrapple, soft pretzels, water ice, Irish potato candy, tastykakes, and the cheesesteak sandwich, which was developed by Italian immigrants.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The Philadelphia area has many establishments that serve cheesesteaks, including restaurants, taverns, delicatessens and pizza parlors.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The originator of the thinly sliced steak sandwich in the 1930s, initially without cheese, is Pat's King of Steaks, which faces its rival Geno's Steaks, founded in 1966, across the intersection of 9th Street and Passyunk Avenue in the Italian Market of South Philadelphia.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] McGillin's Olde Ale House, opened in 1860 on Drury Street in Center City, is the oldest continuously operated tavern in the city.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The City Tavern is a replica of a historic 18th-century building first opened in 1773, demolished in 1854 after a fire, and rebuilt in 1975 on the same site as part of Independence National Historical Park.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The tavern offers authentic 18th-century recipes, served in seven period dining rooms, three wine cellar rooms and an outdoor garden.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The Reading Terminal Market is a historic food market founded in 1893 in the Reading Terminal building, a designated National Historic Landmark.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The enclosed market is one of the oldest and largest markets in the country, hosting over a hundred merchants offering Pennsylvania Dutch specialties, artisan cheese and meat, locally grown groceries, and specialty and ethnic foods.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The traditional Philadelphia accent is considered by some linguists to be the most distinctive accent in North America.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The Philadelphia dialect, which is spread throughout the Philadelphia metropolitan area and South Jersey, is part of a larger Mid-Atlantic American English family, a designation that also includes the Baltimore accent.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Additionally, it shares many similarities with the New York accent.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Owing to over a century of linguistic data collected by researchers at the University of Pennsylvania under sociolinguist William Labov, the Philadelphia dialect has been one of the best-studied forms of American English.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The accent is especially found within the Irish American and Italian American working-class neighborhoods.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Philadelphia also has its own unique collection of neologisms and slang terms.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The Philadelphia Orchestra is generally considered one of the top five orchestras in the United States.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The orchestra performs at the Kimmel Center and has a summer concert series at the Mann Center for the Performing Arts.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Opera Philadelphia performs at the nation's oldest continually operating opera house—the Academy of Music.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The Philadelphia Boys Choir & Chorale has performed its music all over the world.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The Philly Pops plays orchestral versions of popular jazz, swing, Broadway, and blues songs at the Kimmel Center and other venues within the mid-Atlantic region.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The Curtis Institute of Music is one of the world's premier conservatories and among the most selective institutes of higher education in the nation.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Philadelphia has played a prominent role in the music of the United States.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The culture of American popular music has been influenced by significant contributions of Philadelphia area musicians and producers, in both the recording and broadcasting industries.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] In 1952, the teen dance party program called *Bandstand* premiered on local television, hosted by Bob Horn.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The show was renamed *American Bandstand* in 1957, when it began national syndication on ABC, hosted by Dick Clark and produced in Philadelphia until 1964 when it moved to Los Angeles.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Promoters marketed youthful musical artists known as teen idols to appeal to the young audience.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Philadelphia-born singers, including Frankie Avalon, James Darren, Eddie Fisher, Fabian Forte, Bobby Rydell, and South Philly-raised Chubby Checker, topped the music charts, establishing a clean-cut rock and roll image.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Philly soul music of the late 1960s–1970s is a highly produced version of soul music which led to later forms of popular music such as disco and urban contemporary rhythm and blues.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Kennedy Stadium was the American venue for the Live Aid concert.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The city also hosted the Live 8 concert, which attracted about 700,000 people to the Benjamin Franklin Parkway on July 2, 2005.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Philadelphia has one of the nation's richest histories in professional sports, dating back to the mid-19th century.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Its first professional sports team, the Philadelphia Athletics, a professional baseball team, was founded in 1860.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The Athletics were initially an amateur league team that turned professional in 1871.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] In 1876, the Athletics joined with seven other teams in founding the National League, now the longest continuously operating league in world sports.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The Phillies, formed in 1883 as the Quakers and renamed in 1884, are the oldest team continuously playing under the same name in the same city in the history of American professional sports.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The Philadelphia metro area is also home to the Philadelphia Union of Major League Soccer (MLS), plays their home games at Subaru Park, a soccer-specific stadium in Chester, Pennsylvania.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Philadelphia was the second of eight U.S. cities to win titles in all four major leagues, the MLB, NFL, NHL, and NBA.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] It won a title in soccer in the now-defunct North American Soccer League in 1973.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Following the 76ers' victory over the Los Angeles Lakers in the 1983 NBA Finals, however, the city's professional teams and their fans endured 25 years without a championship in any professional sport until the Phillies won the 2008 World Series, defeating the Tampa Bay Rays.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] In 2004, during the city's championship drought, ESPN placed Philadelphia second on its list of "The Fifteen Most Tortured Sports Cities".
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The city's sports fans are often both praised and sometimes derided.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] In 2011, for instance, *GQ* magazine named Eagles and Phillies fans the nation's worst professional sports fans, describing them as the "Meanest Fans in America" in summarizing repeated incidents of their drunken behavior and long history of booing.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] After the Phillies won the 2008 World Series, nine years passed without a championship until the Eagles won their first Super Bowl following the 2017 season, defeating the New England Patriots in Super Bowl LII.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Seven seasons later, following the 2024 season, the Eagles won their second Super Bowl, defeating the Kansas City Chiefs in Super Bowl LIX.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Philadelphia is home to professional, semi-professional, and elite amateur teams in multiple other sports, including cricket, rugby league, and rugby union.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Major running events in the city include the Penn Relays, the Philadelphia Marathon, and the Broad Street Run.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The Collegiate Rugby Championship is played annually each June at Talen Energy Stadium in Chester.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The city also has a rich history in rowing, which has been popular in Philadelphia since the 18th century.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] On Boathouse Row, a symbol of Philadelphia's rich rowing history, each Big Five member has its own boathouse.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The regattas are held on the Schuylkill River and organized by Schuylkill Navy, an association of area rowing clubs that has produced numerous Olympic rowers.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The Philadelphia Spinners were a professional ultimate team in Major League Ultimate (MLU) until 2016.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The Spinners were one of the original eight teams of the American Ultimate Disc League (AUDL), which was founded in 2012.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] They played at Franklin Field and won the inaugural AUDL championship and the final MLU championship in 2016.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The MLU was suspended indefinitely by its investors in December 2016.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] As of 2018, the Philadelphia Phoenix continue to play in the AUDL.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Philadelphia is home to the Philadelphia Big 5, a group of five NCAA Division I college basketball programs, including La Salle, Penn, Saint Joseph's, Temple, and Villanova universities.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The sixth NCAA Division I school in Philadelphia is Drexel University.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] La Salle won the 1954 championship of the NCAA Division I men's basketball tournament.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Villanova won the 1985, 2016, and 2018 NCAA Division I men's basketball tournaments.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Philadelphia was one of the eleven US host cities for the 2026 FIFA World Cup.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] All county functions were assumed by the city in 1952.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The city has been coterminous with the county since 1854.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Philadelphia's 1952 Home Rule Charter was written by the City Charter Commission, which was created by the Pennsylvania General Assembly in an act of April 1949, and a city ordinance of June 1949.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The existing city council received a proposed draft in February 1951, and the electors approved it in an election held in April 1951.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The first elections under the new Home Rule Charter were held in November 1951, and the newly elected officials took office in January 1952.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The city uses the strong-mayor version of the mayor–council form of government, which is led by one mayor in whom executive authority is vested.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The mayor has the authority to appoint and dismiss members of all boards and commissions without the approval of the city council.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Elected at-large, the mayor is limited to two consecutive four-year terms, but can run for the position again after an intervening term.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Philadelphia County is coterminous with the First Judicial District of Pennsylvania.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The Philadelphia County Court of Common Pleas is the trial court of general jurisdiction for the city, hearing felony-level criminal cases and civil suits above the minimum jurisdictional limit of $10,000.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The court has appellate jurisdiction over rulings from the Municipal and Traffic Courts, and some administrative agencies and boards.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The trial division has 70 commissioned judges elected by the voters, along with about one thousand other employees.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The court has a family division with 25 judges and an orphans' court with three judges.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] As of 2018, the city's District Attorney is Larry Krasner, a Democrat.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The last Republican to hold the office is Ronald D.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Castille, who left in 1991 and later served as the Chief Justice of the Pennsylvania Supreme Court from 2008 to 2014.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The Philadelphia Municipal Court handles traffic cases, misdemeanor and felony criminal cases with maximum incarceration of five years, and civil cases involving $12,000 or less ($15,000 in real estate and school tax cases), and all landlord-tenant disputes.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The municipal court has 27 judges elected by the voters.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Pennsylvania's three appellate courts also have sittings in Philadelphia.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The Supreme Court of Pennsylvania, the court of last resort in the state, regularly hears arguments in Philadelphia City Hall.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The Superior Court of Pennsylvania and the Commonwealth Court of Pennsylvania also sit in Philadelphia several times a year.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Judges for these courts are elected at large.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The state Supreme Court and Superior Court have deputy prothonotary offices in Philadelphia.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Philadelphia is home to the federal United States District Court for the Eastern District of Pennsylvania and the Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit, both of which are housed in the James A.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The current mayor is Cherelle Parker who won the election in November 2023.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Parker's predecessor, Jim Kenney, served two terms from 2016 to January 2024.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Parker is a member of the Democratic Party.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] For over seven decades, since 1952, every Philadelphia mayor has been a Democrat.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Philadelphia City Council is the legislative branch which consists of ten council members representing individual districts and seven members elected at-large, all of whom are elected to four-year terms.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Democrats are currently the majority and hold 14 seats including nine of the ten districts and five at-large seats.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Republicans hold one seat: the Northeast-based Tenth District.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The Working Families Party holds two at-large seats making them the council's minority party.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The current council president is Kenyatta Johnson.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Philadelphia's political structure consists of a system of wards and divisions.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] There are 66 wards with 11 to 51 divisions each for a total of 1703 divisions.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Each division elects two committee people who are supposed to live within the division boundaries, and committee people select a leader for their ward.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Democrats and Republicans elect their own committee people every four years.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The committee person's role is to serve as a point of contact between voters and party officials and help get out the vote.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Most wards are closed which means the ward leader makes sole endorsement decisions; open wards allow committee people to weigh in on these decisions.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] There are groups and individuals who are working to elect ward leaders who promote an open ward system.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Philadelphia had historically been a bastion of the Republican Party from the American Civil War until the mid-1930s.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] In 1856, the first Republican National Convention was held at Musical Fund Hall at 808 Locust Street in Philadelphia.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Democratic registrations increased after the Great Depression; however, the city was not carried by Democrat Franklin D.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Roosevelt in his landslide victory of 1932, as Pennsylvania was one of only six states won by Republican Herbert Hoover.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Voter turnout surged from 600,000 in 1932 to nearly 900,000 in 1936 and Roosevelt carried Philadelphia with over 60% of the vote.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Philadelphia has voted Democratic in every presidential election since 1936.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] In 2008, Democrat Barack Obama drew 83% of the city's vote.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Obama's win was even larger in 2012, capturing 85% of the vote.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] In 2016, Democrat Hillary Clinton won 82% of the vote.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] All three representatives are Democrats, though Republicans still have some support in the city, primarily in the Northeast.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Sam Katz ran competitive mayoral races as the Republican nominee in 1999 and 2003, losing to Democrat John Street both times.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Pennsylvania's longest-serving Senator, Arlen Specter, was an alumnus of the University of Pennsylvania who opened his first law practice in Philadelphia.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Specter served as a Republican from 1981 and as a Democrat from 2009, losing that party's primary in 2010 and leaving office in January 2011.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] He was assistant counsel on the Warren Commission in 1964 and the city's district attorney from 1966 to 1974.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Philadelphia has hosted various national conventions, including in 1848 (Whig), 1856 (Republican), 1872 (Republican), 1900 (Republican), 1936 (Democratic), 1940 (Republican), 1948 (Republican), 1948 (Progressive), 2000 (Republican), and 2016 (Democratic).
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Philadelphia has been home to one vice president, George M.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Dallas, and one general of the American Civil War, George B.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] McClellan, who won his party's nomination for president but lost in the general election to Abraham Lincoln in 1864.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Vice President Joe Biden chose Philadelphia to be his 2020 U.S. presidential campaign headquarters.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] "Green Cities, Clean Water" is an environmental policy initiative based in Philadelphia that has shown promising results in mitigating the effects of climate change.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The researchers on the policy have stated that despite such promising plans of green infrastructure building, "the city is forecasted to grow warmer, wetter, and more urbanized over the century, runoff and local temperatures will increase on average throughout the city".
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Each of those seven districts recorded more than a thousand violent crimes in 2014.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The lowest rates of violent crime occurred in Center City, South Philadelphia, the Far Northeast, and Roxborough districts, the latter of which includes Manayunk.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Philadelphia had 500, 503 according to some sources, murders in 1990, a rate of 31.5 per 100,000.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] An average of about 400 murders occurred each year for most of the 1990s.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The murder count dropped in 2002 to 288, then rose to 406 by 2006, before dropping slightly to 392 in 2007.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] A few years later, Philadelphia began to see a rapid decline in homicides and violent crime.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] In 2013, the city had 246 murders, which is a decrease of nearly 40% since 2006.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The homicide rate rose to 280 in 2015, then fell slightly to 277 in 2016, before rising again to 317 in 2017.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Homicides increased dramatically in the late 2010s/early 2020s, reaching 499 homicides in 2020 and surpassing the 1990 "record" in 2021, with 501st murder on November 27 and 510 by the end of the month.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Phillie ended the year with 562 murders, an all-time record.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] It dropped in 2022 to 514, and significantly further again in 2023, to 410.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] In 2006, Philadelphia's homicide rate of 27.7 per 100,000 people was the highest of the country's 10 most populous cities.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] In 2012, Philadelphia had the fourth-highest homicide rate among the country's most populous cities.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The rate dropped to 16 homicides per 100,000 residents by 2014 placing Philadelphia as the sixth-highest city in the country.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The number of shootings in the city has declined significantly since the early years of the 21st century.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Shooting incidents peaked at 1,857 in 2006 before declining nearly 44 percent to 1,047 shootings in 2014.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Major crimes have decreased gradually since a peak in 2006 when 85,498 major crimes were reported.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The number of reported major crimes fell 11 percent in three years to 68,815 occurrences in 2014.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Violent crimes, which include homicide, rape, aggravated assault, and robbery, decreased 14 percent in three years to 15,771 occurrences in 2014.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] In 2014, Philadelphia enacted an ordinance decriminalizing the possession of less than 30 grams of marijuana or eight grams of hashish; the ordinance gave police officers the discretion to treat possession of these amounts as a civil infraction punishable by a $25 ticket, rather than a crime.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] At the time, Philadelphia was at the largest city in the nation to decriminalize the possession of marijuana.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] From 2013 to 2018, marijuana arrests in the city dropped by more than 85%.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The purchase or sale of marijuana remains a criminal offense in Philadelphia.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The Philadelphia Fire Department provides fire protection and emergency medical services (EMS).
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The department's official mission is to protect public safety by quick and professional response to emergencies and the promotion of sound emergency prevention measures.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Education in Philadelphia is provided by many private and public institutions.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The School District of Philadelphia is the local school district, operating public schools, in all of the city.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The Philadelphia School District is the eighth-largest school district in the nation with 142,266 students in 218 traditional public schools and 86 charter schools as of 2014.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The city's K-12 enrollment in district–run schools dropped from 156,211 students in 2010 to 130,104 students in 2015.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] During the same time period, the enrollment in charter schools increased from 33,995 students in 2010 to 62,358 students in 2015.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] This consistent drop in enrollment led the city to close 24 of its public schools in 2013.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] During the 2014 school year, the city spent an average of $12,570 per pupil, below the average among comparable urban school districts.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Graduation rates among district-run schools, meanwhile, steadily increased in the ten years from 2005.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] In 2005, Philadelphia had a district graduation rate of 52%.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] This number increased to 65% in 2014, still below the national and state averages.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Scores on the state's standardized test, the Pennsylvania System of School Assessment (PSSA) trended upward from 2005 to 2011 but subsequently decreased.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] In 2005, the district-run schools scored an average of 37.4% on math and 35.5% on reading.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The city's schools reached their peak scores in 2011 with 59.0% on math and 52.3% on reading.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] In 2014, the scores dropped significantly to 45.2% on math and 42.0% on reading.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Of the city's public high schools, including charter schools, only four performed above the national average on the SAT (1497 out of 2400) in 2014: Masterman, Central, Girard Academic Music Program, and MaST Community Charter School.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] All other district-run schools were below average.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] is the city's largest university by enrollment.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Medical and research facilities of the University of Pennsylvania School of Medicine and the Children's Hospital of Philadelphia.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Philadelphia has the third-largest student concentration on the East Coast, with more than 120,000 college and university students enrolled within the city and nearly 300,000 in the metropolitan area.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] More than 80 colleges, universities, trade, and specialty schools are in the Philadelphia region.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] One of the founding members of the Association of American Universities is in the city, the University of Pennsylvania, an Ivy League institution with claims to be the first university in the United States.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The city's largest university by student enrollment is Temple University, followed by Drexel University.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The city's nationally ranked research universities comprise the University of Pennsylvania, Temple University, Drexel University, and Thomas Jefferson University.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Hospitals, universities, and higher education research institutions in Philadelphia's four congressional districts received more than $252 million in National Institutes of Health grants in 2015.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Philadelphia's two major daily newspapers are *The Philadelphia Inquirer*, first published in 1829—the third-oldest surviving daily newspaper in the country—and the *Philadelphia Daily News*, first published in 1925.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The *Daily News* has been published as an edition of the *Inquirer* since 2009.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Recent owners of the *Inquirer* and *Daily News* have included Knight Ridder, The McClatchy Company, and Philadelphia Media Holdings, with the latter organization declaring bankruptcy in 2010.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] After two years of financial struggle, the newspapers were sold to Interstate General Media in 2012.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The two newspapers had a combined daily circulation of 306,831 and a Sunday circulation of 477,313 in 2013, the 18th-largest circulation in the country, and their collective website, Philly.com, was ranked 13th in popularity among online U.S. newspapers by Alexa Internet the same year.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Student-run newspapers include the University of Pennsylvania's *The Daily Pennsylvanian*, Temple University's *The Temple News*, and Drexel University's *The Triangle*.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The first experimental radio license was issued in Philadelphia in August 1912 to St.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] The first commercial AM radio stations began broadcasting in 1922: first WIP, then owned by Gimbels department store, followed by WFIL, then owned by Strawbridge & Clothier department store, and WOO, a defunct station owned by Wanamaker's department store, as well as WCAU and WDAS.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] As of 2018, the FCC lists 28 FM and 11 AM stations for Philadelphia.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Philadelphia is served by three non-commercial public radio stations: WHYY-FM (NPR), WRTI-FM (classical and jazz), and WXPN-FM (adult alternative music).
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] In the 1930s, W3XE, an experimental station owned by Philco, was the Delaware Valley's first television station.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] In 1939, the station became the nation's first NBC affiliate, and later became KYW-TV.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] In 1952, WFIL, later renamed WPVI, premiered the television show *Bandstand*, which later became the nationally broadcast *American Bandstand* hosted by Dick Clark.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] In the 1960s, WCAU, WFIL-TV, and WHYY-TV were founded.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p02] Additionally, sister company Comcast Spectacor owns the Xfinity Mobile Arena, Stateside Live! and the Philadelphia Flyers, and will own the replacement arena currently scheduled for a 2031 completion.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] Beginning in the 1980s, large sections of the SEPTA Regional Rail service to the far suburbs of Philadelphia were discontinued due to a lack of funding for equipment and infrastructure maintenance.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] Philadelphia's 30th Street Station is a major railroad station on Amtrak's Northeast Corridor with 4.4 million passengers in 2017 making it the third-busiest station in the country after New York City's Pennsylvania Station and Washington's Union Station.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] 30th Street Station offers access to Amtrak, SEPTA, and NJ Transit lines.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] Over 12 million SEPTA and NJ Transit rail commuters use the station each year, and more than 100,000 people on an average weekday.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] Philadelphia International Airport (PHL), the larger of the two, is 7 mi (11 km) south-southwest of Center City on the boundary with Delaware County, and provides scheduled domestic and international air service.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] As of 2023, Philadelphia International Airport is the 21st-busiest airport in the nation with over 13.6 million passengers.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] It is also among the world's busiest airports measured by traffic movements, including takeoffs and landings.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] Over 30 million passengers pass through the airport annually on 25 airlines, including all major domestic carriers.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] The airport has nearly 500 daily departures to over 120 destinations worldwide.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] SEPTA's Airport Line provides direct service between Center City railroad stations and Philadelphia International Airport.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] Philadelphia's second major airport, Northeast Philadelphia Airport (PNE), is a general aviation relief airport in Northeast Philadelphia, which provides general and corporate aviation.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] William Penn planned Philadelphia with numbered streets traversing north and south, and streets named for trees, including Chestnut, Walnut, and Mulberry (since renamed Arch) Streets, traversing east and west.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] The two main streets were named Broad Street, the north–south artery, later designated Pennsylvania Route 611, and High Street, the east–west artery, which was later renamed Market Street, converging at Centre Square which later became the site of City Hall.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] The city is served by Interstate 76, also known as the Schuylkill Expressway, which runs along the Schuylkill River, intersecting the Pennsylvania Turnpike at King of Prussia and providing access to Harrisburg and points west.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] Interstate 676, also known as Vine Street Expressway, links I-95 and I-76 through Center City, running below street level between the eastbound and westbound lanes of Vine Street.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] Entrance and exit ramps for the Benjamin Franklin Bridge are near the eastern end of the expressway just west of the I-95 interchange.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] Roosevelt Boulevard and Expressway, also known as U.S.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] 1, connects Northeast Philadelphia with Center City via I-76 through Fairmount Park.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] Woodhaven Road, also known as Route 63, and Cottman Avenue, also known as Route 73, serve the neighborhoods of Northeast Philadelphia, running between I-95 and the Roosevelt Boulevard.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] Fort Washington Expressway, also known as Route 309, extends north from the city's northern border, serving Montgomery and Bucks Counties.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] Route 30, also known as Lancaster Avenue, extends west from West Philadelphia to Lancaster.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] Interstate 476, locally called the Blue Route, traverses Delaware County, bypassing the city to the west and serving the city's western suburbs, providing a direct route to Allentown, the Poconos, and points north.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] Interstate 276, the Pennsylvania Turnpike's Delaware River Extension, is a bypass and commuter route north of the city, which links to the New Jersey Turnpike and New York City.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] Delaware River Port Authority operates four bridges in the Philadelphia area, each of which crosses the Delaware River to South Jersey: Walt Whitman Bridge (I-76), the Benjamin Franklin Bridge (I-676 and U.S.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] 30), Betsy Ross Bridge (New Jersey Route 90), and Commodore Barry Bridge (U.S.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] 322) in Delaware County, south of the city.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] The Burlington County Bridge Commission maintains two additional bridges that cross the Delaware River.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] Tacony–Palmyra Bridge connects PA Route 73 in the Tacony section of Northeast Philadelphia with New Jersey Route 73 in Palmyra in Burlington County.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] Burlington–Bristol Bridge connects NJ Route 413/U.S.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] Route 130 in Burlington, New Jersey with PA Route 413/U.S.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] 13 in Bristol Township, north of Philadelphia.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] The Greyhound terminal is at 1001 Filbert Street (at 10th Street) in Center City, southeast of the Pennsylvania Convention Center and south of Chinatown.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] Several other bus operators provide service at the Greyhound terminal including Fullington Trailways, Martz Trailways, Peter Pan Bus Lines, and NJ Transit buses.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] Other intercity bus services include Megabus with stops at 30th Street Station and the visitor center for Independence Hall, BoltBus (operated by Greyhound) at 30th Street Station, OurBus at various stops in the city.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] Since the early days of rail transportation in the United States, Philadelphia has served as a hub for several major rail companies, particularly the Pennsylvania Railroad and the Reading Railroad.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] The Pennsylvania Railroad first operated Broad Street Station, then 30th Street Station and Suburban Station, and the Reading Railroad operated Reading Terminal, now part of the Pennsylvania Convention Center.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] The two companies also operated competing commuter rail systems in the area.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] The two systems now operate as a single system under the control of SEPTA, the regional transit authority.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] Additionally, the PATCO Speedline subway system and NJ Transit's Atlantic City Line operate successor services to South Jersey.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] In 1911, Philadelphia had nearly 4,000 electric trolleys running on 86 lines.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] In 2005, SEPTA reintroduced trolley service to the Girard Avenue Line, Route 15.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] SEPTA operates six subway-surface trolleys that run on street-level tracks in West Philadelphia and subway tunnels in Center City, along with two surface trolleys in adjacent suburbs.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] Philadelphia is a regional hub of the federally-owned Amtrak system, with 30th Street Station being a primary stop on the Washington-Boston Northeast Corridor and the Keystone Corridor to Harrisburg and Pittsburgh.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] 30th Street also serves as a major station for services via the Pennsylvania Railroad's former Pennsylvania Main Line to Chicago.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] As of 2018, 30th Street is Amtrak's third-busiest station in the country, after New York City and Washington.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] In 1815, Philadelphia began sourcing its water via the Fairmount Water Works on the Schuylkill River, the nation's first major urban water supply system.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] In 1909, the Water Works was decommissioned as the city transitioned to modern sand filtration methods.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] Philadelphia Water Department (PWD) provides drinking water, wastewater collection, and stormwater services for Philadelphia, as well as surrounding counties.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] PWD draws about 57 percent of its drinking water from the Delaware River and the balance from the Schuylkill River.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] The city has two filtration plants on the Schuylkill River and one on the Delaware River.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] The three plants can treat up to 546 million gallons of water per day, while the total storage capacity of the combined plant and distribution system exceeds one billion gallons.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] The wastewater system consists of three water pollution control plants, 21 pumping stations, and about 3,657 miles (5,885 km) of sewers.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] PECO is the largest electric and natural gas utility in the state with 472 power substations and nearly 23,000 miles (37,000 km) of electric transmission and distribution lines and 12,000 miles (19,000 km) of natural gas transmission, distribution, and service lines.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] Philadelphia Gas Works (PGW), overseen by the Pennsylvania Public Utility Commission, is the nation's largest municipally owned natural gas utility.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] PGW serves over 500,000 homes and businesses in the Philadelphia area.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] Founded in 1836, the company came under city ownership in 1987 and has been providing the majority of gas distributed within city limits.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] In 2014, the City Council refused to conduct hearings on a $1.86 billion sale of PGW, part of a two-year effort that was proposed by the mayor.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] The refusal led to the prospective buyer terminating its offer.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] Southeastern Pennsylvania was assigned the 215 area code in 1947 when the North American Numbering Plan of the Bell System went into effect.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] The geographic area covered by the code was split nearly in half in 1994 when area code 610 was created, with the city and its northern suburbs retaining 215.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] Overlay area code 267 was added to the 215 service area in 1997, and 484 was added to the 610 area in 1999.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] A plan in 2001 to introduce a third overlay code to both service areas, area code 445 to 215 and area code 835 to 610, was delayed and later rescinded.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] Area code 445 was implemented as an overlay for area codes 215 and 267 starting on February 3, 2018.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] Philadelphia has eight official sister cities as designated by the Citizen Diplomacy International (CDI) of Philadelphia: Philadelphia has dedicated landmarks to its sister cities.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] The Sister Cities Park, a site of 0.5 acres (0.20 ha) at 18th and Benjamin Franklin Parkway in Logan Square, was dedicated in June 1976.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] The park was built to commemorate Philadelphia's first two sister city relationships, with Tel Aviv and Florence.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] Toruń Triangle, honoring the sister city relationship with Toruń, Poland, was constructed in 1976, west of the United Way building at 18th Street and Benjamin Franklin Parkway.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] Sister Cities Park was redesigned and reopened in 2012, featuring an interactive fountain honoring Philadelphia's sister and partnership cities, a café and visitor center, children's play area, outdoor garden, boat pond, and a pavilion built to environmentally friendly standards.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] The Chinatown Gate, erected in 1984 and crafted by artisans from Tianjin, stands astride 10th Street, on the north side of its intersection with Arch Street, as a symbol of the sister city relationship.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] The CDI of Philadelphia has participated in the U.S.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] Department of State's "Partners for Peace" project with Mosul, Iraq, and in accepting visiting delegations from dozens of other countries.
[src:philadelphia/philadelphia-p03] In September 2025, John Moolenaar, chair of the United States House Select Committee on Strategic Competition between the United States and the Chinese Communist Party, requested that Philadelphia review its sister city agreement with Tianjin.
